`ctx-verify/src` is the whole implementation of the `ctx-verify` binary: a tool that runs a fixed set of checks (fmt, clippy, tests, contracts, architecture, etc.) through an injectable process boundary and emits one capped, schema-stable JSON (or terse-text) report. Depending on this crate's public surface (`cli::run`, `checks::run_selected`, `runner::Runner`) gets you a deterministic, gate-fails-closed verification pass; the interesting work happens inside these layers, not above them.

The layering is strict and one-directional: `main.rs` → `cli.rs` → `checks.rs` → `checks/specs.rs` for the check table, with `runner.rs` as the sole process-spawning seam and `parse.rs`/`model.rs` shared beneath everything for turning tool output into `Diagnostic`/`Report` values. A new check touches three places together — `checks/specs.rs` (table entry + parser choice), `parse.rs` (new parser if none of the four existing flavors fit), and `model.rs` if the report shape needs to change — never `runner.rs` directly. `checks.rs`'s self-heal logic (regen-then-recheck-once for `contracts`/`architecture`) is gated by the ADR-022 allowlist that lives in `specs.rs::regen_command`, so extending auto-fix means checking that file, not adding a match arm in `checks.rs`.

Two invariants span the whole crate: (1) status precedence `Errored > Fail > Skipped > Pass` is enforced only in `model.rs::Report::new` and never duplicated elsewhere, so a missing tool or infra failure can never read as a pass; (2) a failing/skipped/errored check is never silently empty — `failure_hint`, `CheckReport::skipped`, and `CheckReport::errored` all synthesize a diagnostic if the parser found none. `cli.rs`'s `CONTRACT` constant is externally load-bearing (drives generated doc blocks checked by the crate's own `contracts` battery) — changing its wording requires regenerating those docs.

`error.rs` supplies the single `CheckError` enum consumed by both `runner.rs` and `cli.rs`'s I/O paths; `lib.rs` only wires modules together.

No `intent.md` exists to check divergence against.